<TITLE> Pakistan court speeds Musharraf case on crisis talk </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 ISLAMABAD, Nov 2 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Pakistan's Supreme Court said it will reconvene hearing challenges to President Pervez Musharraf's re-election on Monday, backtracking on an earlier plan to take up the case again on Nov. 12. That would have been just three days before Musharraf's current term ends. Nuclear-armed Pakistan is going through a period of intense uncertainty, and the court's dallying had been a factor fuelling rumours Musharraf could invoke emergency powers and call off a vote due in January which is supposed to transform the country into a civilian-led democracy. "The court will not take any blame for the controversy being created," said Justice Javed Iqbal, head of the 11-member bench hearing the objections to Musharraf contesting the presidency while still army chief, as proceedings were wrapped up on Friday. He added that efforts would be made to conclude the case in the shortest possible time. The stock market steadied on Friday, recovering almost one percent by lunchtime after dropping nearly three percent the previous day, as nervous investors retreated from one of Asia's best performing markets this year. The talk of an emergency or martial law, also had prompted US Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice to say any such move would be opposed by the United States and that elections should go ahead next year. "I am not going to get into the details of our conversations but I think it would be quite obvious that the United States would not be supportive of extra-constitutional means," Rice told journalists before a refuelling stop in Ireland on her way to Turk
